4-6. sie . . . incipe. See on 9. 30. Here the wish is adapted to the legend of Arethusa flying from Alpheus, related in A. 3. 694 (see Classical Dict. s. v. ARETHUSA). The poet prays that her pure stream may keep undefiled by contact with the briny waters. (See Shelley's Arethusa in Appendix.) Doris, as the wife of Nereus, stands for the sea, like ‘ Nerea ' in 6. 35. sollicitos as causing anxiety. Cp. Ov. Her. 1. 12 ‘ res est solliciti plena timoris amor.’
